  "prompt": "What is the difference between calcium carbonate salt and table salt?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between calcium carbonate salt and table salt:\n\nCalcium Carbonate Salt (CaCO3):\n- Chemical composition: Calcium, carbon, and oxygen\n- White, powdery mineral\n- Found naturally in limestone, chalk, and marble\n- Used in antacids, dietary supplements, and construction materials\n- Not typically used for food seasoning\n- Alkaline in nature\n\nTable Salt (NaCl):\n- Chemical composition: Sodium and chloride\n- White, crystalline substance\n- Typically mined or extracted from seawater\n- Used for seasoning and food preservation\n- Common in cooking and food preparation\n- Salty taste\n- Neutral pH\n\nPrimary differences:\n1. Chemical composition\n2. Elemental components\n3. Uses\n4. Physical properties\n5. Taste\n6. pH characteristics\n\nBoth are considered \"salts\" in chemical terms, but they have very different properties and applications.",
